   =20
 =20
 Credit Suisse, Cash and Cocaine Converge in Historic Conviction. Inside Ci=
tigroup=E2=80=99s Attempt to Rally Wall Street to Pressure Gun Sellers. Mor=
e Hedge Funds Are Betting Against Tether as Crypto Melts Down. Trump-Tied  =
SPAC Says New York Grand Jury Subpoenaed Its Board. BP  Paid Rural Mexicans=
 a =E2=80=9CPittance=E2=80=9D for Wall Street=E2=80=99s Favorite Climate So=
lution. Pension Funds Plunge Into Riskier Bets=E2=80=94Just as Markets Are =
Struggling. Crypto Meltdown Drags  Lending Returns From 25,000% to Almost Z=
ero. How Elon Musk Helped Lift the Ceiling on C.E.O. Pay.=C2=A0UK Treasury =
takes a stake in sex party planner Killing Kittens.If you'd like to get=C2=
=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=
=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other=
 great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] A subplot in the House Financ=
ial Services=C2=A0Committee report concerns how Robinhood calculates the pa=
yment for order flow that it gets from market makers. =E2=80=9CMost other b=
roker-dealers calculate PFOF rebates as a flat fee per share, whereas=C2=A0=
 Robinhood calculates PFOF rebate rates based on the spread between the pur=
chase and sale price of each security at the time of executing a=C2=A0trade=
 on behalf of a customer.=E2=80=9D At volatile times, spreads blow out, bec=
ause market making is riskier: If the stock is going to move against you by=
 $1 every time you trade, you need to charge a spread of at least $1. Robin=
hood=E2=80=99s formula charges PFOF as, essentially, a percentage of the pu=
blic-market spread. When the spread is very wide because market making is v=
ery risky, market making is not particularly profitable (you make a lot of =
money on spreads but lose it on adverse selection), but Robinhood *charges*=
 its market makers more. The market makers did not love this, and there is =
a lot of discussion in the report about how Citadel Securities pushed back =
to lower its PFOF payments to Robinhood. (=E2=80=9CAn employee for Citadel =
Securities described Robinhood=E2=80=99s PFOF rebates as a runaway freight =
train in the days leading up to January 28, 2021.=E2=80=9D) Robinhood got a=
nnoyed at Citadel but also proposed to cap PFOF at $0.003 per share in the =
meme stocks.=C2=A0[2]=C2=A0This cash is Robinhood=E2=80=99s cash, to guaran=
tee *its* obligation, as a clearing broker, to the clearinghouse. Separatel=
y, Robinhood will want to make sure that its customers are good for their o=
bligations to buy the stocks they agreed to buy, which it might do by, for =
example, requiring them to have cash in their accounts before doing trades,=
 etc. (Not always =E2=80=94=C2=A0retail brokers offer margin trading, and s=
ometimes let you trade before your deposits have cleared, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but broadly speaking this is a solvable sort of risk management problem =
for the retail brokerage.) But Robinhood can=E2=80=99t just take the cash i=
n its customers=E2=80=99 accounts and hand it over to the clearinghouse to =
guarantee its obligations; that cash belongs to the customers.[3] I assume.=
 I am not completely sure about this =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Journal reported it=
 as a rumor, and Euroclear =E2=80=9Cdidn=E2=80=99t immediately respond to a=
 request for comment=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the basic principle works =
even if this specific case is wrong. Russia has tried to send=C2=A0money to=
 various foreign intermediaries so it can get to bondholders, and the inter=
mediaries are subject to US and European jurisdiction and don=E2=80=99t pas=
s it along.[4] This is a hard part, I guess? The transfers here might be tr=
icky. But, for instance, Russia is still getting hard currency by selling o=
il, which is allowed under the sanctions regime; presumably it can leave so=
me of that money in a lightly guarded place and say =E2=80=9Cpsst bondholde=
rs look over here.=E2=80=9D
