10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Robinhood=E2=80=99s crazy week</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Markets Inc. is in the busin=
ess of getting people to trade stock (and options, and cryptocurrencies) on=
 their phones. The more people who sign up for accounts, and the more they =
trade, the happier Robinhood is. The way it makes money is that each time i=
ts customers trade stocks (or options, or cryptocurrencies), Robinhood send=
s their order to a market maker, and the market maker pays Robinhood a tiny=
 fee for the right to execute the order. Unlike many other retail brokers, =
Robinhood charges these market makers a variable fee that is, roughly speak=
ing, higher for very volatile stocks.[1] So the more people who sign up for=
 Robinhood=E2=80=99s service, and the more they trade, and the more volatil=
e the stocks that they trade are, the more money Robinhood makes.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By this standard, the last week of January 2021 was =
incredibly, incredibly good for Robinhood, an amazingly perfect week. That =
was the height of the GameStop Corp. meme-stock mania: The whole world=E2=
=80=99s attention was focused on the soaring price of GameStop stock, which=
 was leading a lot of people to sign up for Robinhood and trade GameStop, a=
nd GameStop was very volatile and so Robinhood got paid a lot for trading i=
t. Robinhood both increased its future value by signing up a lot of custome=
rs, and increased its present profits by extracting a lot of money from the=
m each day.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was, however, a problem. =
When Robinhood=E2=80=99s customers buy a stock, the trade does not settle r=
ight away: The customer agrees to buy the stock, and the market maker agree=
s to sell it to them, but they don=E2=80=99t actually exchange money for st=
ock until two business days later. There is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/28194419.268588/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjkvcmVkZGl0LXRyYWRlcnMtb24tcm9iaW5ob29k=
LWFyZS1vbi1ib3RoLXNpZGVzLW9mLWdhbWVzdG9wP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZ=
GJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyNy=
Z1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB02a23e70" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> a credit component</a> to the trade: The buyer has to deliver the money i=
n two days, and the seller has to deliver the stock. If the stock shoots up=
 over those two days, you might worry that the seller will back out of the =
deal; if the stock crashes, you might worry that the buyer will back out of=
 the deal. In practice, the stock market deals with this risk through clear=
inghouses: One giant entity (for US stocks, it=E2=80=99s the National Secur=
ities Clearing Corp., a subsidiary of the Depository Trust &amp; Clearing C=
orp.) guarantees all the trades, and clearinghouse members, like Robinhood,=
 post cash with the clearinghouse to guarantee their customers=E2=80=99 tra=
des.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Broadly speaking, Robinhood has to =
post more cash with the clearinghouse as its customers trade more stocks. A=
nd it has to post more cash as those stocks are more volatile: The more lik=
ely it is that a stock will crash or moon, the bigger the credit risk is, s=
o the more money is required.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By this=
 standard, the last week of January 2021 was incredibly <em>bad </em>for Ro=
binhood. The GameStop meme-stock mania caused a lot of its customers to buy=
 GameStop, and caused the price of GameStop to be very volatile, which caus=
ed Robinhood to have to post enormous amounts of cash with the clearinghous=
e, and it happened not to have that cash lying around.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">And so Robinhood=E2=80=99s otherwise great week came shoc=
kingly close to killing it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week the U=
S House Financial Services Committee <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/28194419.268588/aHR0cHM6Ly9maW5hbmNpYWxzZXJ2aWNlcy5ob3Vz=
ZS5nb3YvbmV3cy9kb2N1bWVudHNpbmdsZS5hc3B4P0RvY3VtZW50SUQ9NDA5NTc4/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB289299d4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">released a report</a> about that week at t=
he end of January 2021, and it is fascinating reading. It is mostly about R=
obinhood, and specifically it is about the tension=C2=A0inside Robinhood be=
tween the fact that=C2=A0<em>it was a great week=C2=A0</em>and the fact tha=
t=C2=A0<em>it almost blew up Robinhood</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">So on the one hand, the meme-stock week was great for Robinhood=E2=80=99s=
 growth, and the people whose job it was to make Robinhood grow were excite=
d. On Tuesday, Jan. 26, Elon Musk tweeted =E2=80=9CGamestonk!!,=E2=80=9D wh=
ich of course pushed up interest in trading GameStop on Robinhood. A Robinh=
ood product manager emailed about this: =E2=80=9CFYI massive spike [in Robi=
nhood account openings] in last 30m likely caused by Elon Musk tweet=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe could probably interact with this movement to promote R=
H growth.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But as the week we=
nt on, Robinhood got more nervous, both about its cash needs and about whet=
her its technology was up to all the activity. So here is a discussion =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0at about 11:24 p.m. on Wednesday, Jan. 27 =E2=80=94=C2=A0betwee=
n a brokerage product manager at Robinhood and the firm=E2=80=99s head of d=
ata science:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Product ma=
nager: </strong>conflict brewing</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Pr=
oduct manager: </strong>we have to keep the growth flywheel running</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Product manager:</strong> webull is right =
on our tail</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Head of data science: <=
/strong>haah dont worry, we need to survive first</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They wanted to grow to pull ahead of the competition, =
but growth=C2=A0<em>that week=C2=A0</em>was becoming a problem. Here is how=
 close Robinhood came to blowing up the next day:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the morning of January 28, 2021, Robinhood had appr=
oximately $696 million in collateral already on deposit with the NSCC, leav=
ing it with a collateral deficit of approximately $3 billion, which it was =
required to post to satisfy the NSCC=E2=80=99s clearing fund requirement or=
 risk being in violation of the NSCC=E2=80=99s rules and potentially losing=
 the ability to clear trades for their customers altogether. [President of =
Robinhood=E2=80=99s clearing operation Jim] Swartwout confirmed that this a=
mount came as a surprise to Robinhood and explained to Committee staff that=
 they had anticipated and prepared for the $1.4 billion of collateral depos=
it requirements that represent =E2=80=9Ccore=E2=80=9D charges, but because =
they did not model for Excess Capital Premium charges, Robinhood therefore =
did not expect and had not arranged adequate funding for the additional $2.=
2 billion Excess Capital Premium charge. On the morning of January 28, 2021=
, Jim Swartwout texted [Robinhood Chief Operating Officer] Gretchen Howard =
at 6:29 a.m. EST, writing =E2=80=9CHuge liquidity issue.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, the clearinghouse called=
 Robinhood and said it needed to post about $3 billion to cover its obligat=
ions, and Robinhood didn=E2=80=99t have the money. Ultimately the clearingh=
ouse waived most of the collateral requirement that day, for Robinhood and =
some other firms in similar predicaments. If it hadn=E2=80=99t (emphasis ad=
ded):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Without the NSCC=E2=80=99=
s waiver of Robinhood=E2=80=99s Excess Capital Premium charge, Robinhood=E2=
=80=99s nonpayment would have constituted a =E2=80=9Cserious rule violation=
=E2=80=9D according to the NSCC=E2=80=99s rules.=C2=A0When a clearing-broke=
r cannot deposit the required collateral, the member is in default to the c=
learinghouse and NSCC may =E2=80=9Ccease to act=E2=80=9D for that member un=
der its rules, as the NSCC did for Lehman Brothers on September 24, 2008 an=
d MF Global on October 31, 2011. <strong>When NSCC ceases to act, the clear=
inghouse assumes control of the defaulted member=E2=80=99s portfolio and li=
quidates it.</strong> This is done to limit the risk that the defaulted mem=
ber poses to NSCC and to other nondefaulting NSCC members, who can be subje=
ct to mutualized losses if the collateral already held by NSCC is insuffici=
ent to cover losses on the defaulter=E2=80=99s portfolio. Robinhood leaders=
hip remained aware during the morning of January 28, 2021 that the NSCC cou=
ld effectively eliminate the company=E2=80=99s ability to clear their clien=
t=E2=80=99s trades and liquidate the firm=E2=80=99s holdings.</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That would have been bad! =E2=80=9CHypothet=
ically what happens if a firm can=E2=80=99t meet their morning NSCC margin =
settlement,=E2=80=9D an operations manager asked their former boss that mor=
ning=C2=A0in a text message. Nothing good!=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Robinhood responded to the problem =E2=80=94=C2=A0of not having enoug=
h money to support its explosive growth =E2=80=94 by raising capital, but a=
lso by limiting customer trading in meme stocks, imposing PCO, =E2=80=9Cpos=
ition closing only,=E2=80=9D restrictions to prevent customers from buying =
more GameStop:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Robinhood emp=
loyees worked through Wednesday, January 27, 2021, to code position=C2=A0li=
mits for meme stocks, they struggled with how to frame the trading restrict=
ions to the public and seemed to want to avoid giving their own clients the=
 real reasons for imposing restrictions. A=C2=A0product manager at Robinhoo=
d Financial asked, =E2=80=9CDo we have a customer facing rational we can=C2=
=A0provide?=C2=A0In response, a manager in Robinhood=E2=80=99s brokerage re=
sponded, =E2=80=9CThe real reason is firm risk and us needing to control th=
e velocity of trading. =E2=80=A6But we shouldn=E2=80=99t expose that.=E2=80=
=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also slowed=C2=A0down n=
ew account approvals:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According=
 to Robinhood operations staff, turning off auto approval meant that Robinh=
ood=C2=A0was still =E2=80=9Caccepting applications, but approval is turned =
off. This means a large number of customers (were) still applying but (woul=
dn=E2=80=99t) be approved immediately,=E2=80=9D delaying their ability to=
=C2=A0transact on the platform. The decision to throttle new account creati=
on arose spontaneously on the morning of January 28, 2021.=C2=A0During the =
afternoon of January 28, 2021, Robinhood Director of Account Operations est=
imated that approximately 300,000 customer applications were waiting in the=
 queue to be approved. Robinhood employees discussed when to turn auto appr=
oval back on throughout the day on January 28, 2021 but decided to keep the=
 auto approvals turned off for the remainder of the day due to risk concern=
s associated with increased load on their platform. As a Robinhood employee=
 said in a chat discussing when to resume approving accounts, =E2=80=9Cany =
additional load takes us to the bottom faster.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Ultimately Robinhood=E2=80=99s decision to turn off auto appro=
val had a significant impact on the number of new accounts on its platform.=
 On the morning of January 29, 2021, the next day, Robinhood Financial=E2=
=80=99s Director of Brokerage Risk estimated that the number of customers w=
aiting in the queue for their accounts to be approved had increased to appr=
oximately 730,000.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The meme-st=
ock craze was so good for Robinhood that 430,000 people tried to sign up fo=
r its service overnight! And so bad for Robinhood that it had to ignore all=
 of them.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. It al=
l worked out, I guess. On Jan. 28, Robinhood Financial President David Duss=
eault told the Robinhood team =E2=80=9Cah we will navigate through this nsc=
c issue,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe are to big for them to actually shut us d=
own.=E2=80=9D Never something you want to put in writing, but not exactly w=
rong. The meme-stock craze made Robinhood arguably the most important compa=
ny in finance for a week. It would have been better if Robinhood=E2=80=99s =
explosive success had made it rich and safe, but making it too big to fail =
also worked.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto=
