<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Russian default</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia has international bonds outstan=
ding, and it has the dollars to make payments on them, but it has been bloc=
ked, by sanctions, from making those payments. Yesterday a deadline for mak=
ing some of those payments expired, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/28194419.268588/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjYvcnVzc2lhLWRlZmF1bHRzLW9uLWZvcmVpZ24tZGVidC1mb3It=
Zmlyc3QtdGltZS1zaW5jZS0xOTE4P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB401b718d" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> putting Ru=
ssia officially into default</a> on its bonds. Now what? The Wall Street Jo=
urnal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28194419.268=
588/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zYW5jdGlvbnMtcHVzaC1ydXNzaWEtbmV=
hci1maXJzdC1mb3JlaWduLWRlZmF1bHQtc2luY2UtYm9sc2hldmlrLXJldm9sdXRpb24tMTE2NT=
YyNDgyMTI_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB823c0278" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>has the traditional answer</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">In theory, creditors could try to seize Russian assets abroad, though it =
is unclear what they might go after. Some investors have suggested they mig=
ht claim frozen central-bank reserves or oligarchs=E2=80=99 assets. Bondhol=
ders of Venezuelan debt sought assets of a state-owned oil refiner after th=
e country=E2=80=99s default. In 2013, Argentina hired a private jet for the=
 then-president=E2=80=99s trip to Asia and the Middle East because of the r=
isk of creditors seizing the official aircraft.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI suspect, remembering what happened with Argentina, th=
at the Americans would be keen to have creditors chasing Russian assets all=
 over the world,=E2=80=9D said Paul McNamara, an emerging-market fund manag=
er at GAM. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s basically contracting out the job of going=
 after Russian assets.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Sure. If there is some stash of dollars (or=C2=A0yachts, houses, et=
c.) that belong to Russia, the bondholders could try to seize them. I will =
tell you where one stash of Russian dollars might be. The Journal also repo=
rts:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia has plenty of money=
 from oil and gas sales to pay its foreign debts, which are relatively smal=
l compared with the size of its economy. But allied Western governments hav=
e blocked the Kremlin=E2=80=99s ability to tap foreign bank accounts or use=
 cross-border payment networks to move money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The Treasury Department last month let a prior sanctions exemption expir=
e that had allowed U.S. banks and investors to process and receive payments=
 on existing Russian bonds. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One investo=
r said clearinghouse Euroclear received funds for the May interest payments=
 just before the Treasury=E2=80=99s exemption expiration. But the funds wer=
e frozen there because of sanctions, unable to be forwarded to his account.=
 Lawyers say the bond documents are unclear over whether payments that reac=
hed the clearinghouse, but not the bondholder account, would constitute a f=
ormal default.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Euroclear spokespers=
on didn=E2=80=99t immediately respond to a request for comment.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay. Let=E2=80=99s not focus on the tech=
nical question of whether it counts as a default if the money gets to Euroc=
lear but Euroclear does not (due to sanctions) pass it along to the bondhol=
ders. I just want to make a narrow point here, which is:</p><ul style=3D"li=
st-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">Russia supposedly transferred the $100 million for this=
 payment to Euroclear, where it is stuck.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">The bondholders are now, I guess, looking to seize some Russian ass=
ets abroad.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What about that $100 m=
illion at Euroclear?</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like, Euroclear=
=C2=A0<em>has=C2=A0</em>that money,[3] and the bondholders=C2=A0<em>want=C2=
=A0</em>it, but Euroclear can=E2=80=99t pass it along to them because sanct=
ions prohibit it from passing along interest payments on behalf of Russia. =
But if you utter the right incantations, you can turn that $100 million fro=
m =E2=80=9Ca Russian interest payment=E2=80=9D into =E2=80=9CRussian assets=
 abroad that can be used to satisfy a default judgment.=E2=80=9D And then E=
uroclear could give it to the bondholders. Maybe? Boy is that not legal adv=
ice.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This does not quite work as a matter o=
f=C2=A0arithmetic. Russia has transferred a little bit of money to foreign =
banks and clearinghouses to make interest payments on its bonds, and those =
payments have gotten stuck, and that has led to a default, and in theory th=
at default allows the holders of all of Russia=E2=80=99s billions of dollar=
s of international bonds to accelerate those bonds and demand immediate rep=
ayment. So there could be a rush of all of the bondholders to seize money, =
and the $100 million that might or might not be at Euroclear won=E2=80=99t =
come close to satisfying all of their claims.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Still it is a strange sort of default. You could imagine a financial-eng=
ineering approach:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: =
40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Get all the bon=
dholders together to agree to accelerate the debt and try to seize Russian =
assets abroad.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bondholders als=
o agree to a payment waterfall: Holders of Bond A get the first $X seized, =
and then holders of Bond B get the next $Y, and then holders of Bonds C and=
 D share equally in the next $Z, etc. And $X happens to be the interest pay=
ment due on Bond A next month, and $Y happens to be the amount due on repay=
ment of Bond B at maturity next year, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">On the next interest payment date for Bond A, Russia transfers $X =
to a foreign account at some international bank and says =E2=80=9Chey bondh=
olders come seize our money.=E2=80=9D[4]</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">The bondholders apply to the bank to seize the money and give it to =
the holders of Bond A under the payment waterfall.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">The bank is like =E2=80=9Csure whatever here you go,=C2=A0=
<em>seizing=C2=A0</em>Russian money isn=E2=80=99t sanctioned, in fact it is=
 encouraged.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then Russia =
pays Bond B the same way.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Etc.</li=
></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically you pass the bond payments alo=
ng to the holders as normal, except that instead of calling them =E2=80=9Cb=
ond payments=E2=80=9D you call them =E2=80=9Cassets seized due to accelerat=
ion of the bonds in default.=E2=80=9D The bondholders get paid as normal, b=
ut you get to say that Russia is getting punished for default instead of pa=
ying its debts in the ordinary course. You get to call it a default, but th=
e bondholders get to keep getting paid.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-=
ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
